The Faroe Islands[b] (/ˈfɛəroʊ/ FAIR-oh) (alt. the Faroes) are an archipelago
in the North Atlantic Ocean and an autonomous territory of the Kingdom
of Denmark. Located between Iceland, Norway, and the United Kingdom, the
islands have a population of 54,676 as of August 2023 and a land area of
1,393 km².[10] The official language is Faroese, which is partially mutually
intelligible with Icelandic. The terrain is rugged and sparse, dominated
by fjords and cliffs with sparse vegetation and few trees.